Exports Boosts Czech Day-Ahead Power; Polish Contract Declines

-- B y   M a r e k   S t r z e l e c k i
-- 
2011-05-31T14:58:12Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-31/exports-boosts-czech-day-ahead-power-polish-contract-declines.html
Czech day-ahead power prices rose as
exports increased. The equivalent Polish contract dropped on
lower shipments.  Czech day-ahead power climbed 1.9 percent to 57.80 euros
($83.30) a megawatt-hour, according to broker data compiled by
Bloomberg. Polish electricity for tomorrow declined 0.8 percent
to 213.79 zloty ($77.96) a megawatt-hour, according to Polish
power exchange data compiled by Bloomberg.  Hungarian electricity, traded on the Budapest-based power
exchange, lost 1.4 percent to 58.28 euros a megawatt-hour,
according to the bourse’s website. The equivalent contract in
 Germany , a benchmark for eastern  Europe , fell 1.5 percent to
57.50 euros, broker data show.  The  Czech Republic  has 17,625 megawatts of capacity
installed, according to Bloomberg data. The country was
exporting 1,495 megawatts of power to Germany between 1 p.m. and
2 p.m., according to  Entsoe , the European Transmission System
Operators transparency platform. Exports of Polish electricity
were set to decline tomorrow as more maintenance is planned,
according to  PSE Operator , the country’s transmission system
operator.  Bloomberg tracks power prices from brokers including GFI
Group Inc., ICAP Plc, Spectron Group Ltd., Tradition Financial
Services and Tullett Prebon Plc. Brokers handle the majority of
trading in Europe’s electricity markets.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Marek Strzelecki in Warsaw at 
 mstrzelecki1@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Stephen Voss at   sev@bloomberg.net  